ce:section.ce:para:
Synthesis of unique N-doped CDs was reported by Zhang et al. following a simple hydrothermal method and by using N-methyl-2-pyrrolidone (NMP) as a precursor [66]. The probe has the potential for trace detection of Fe3+ and F-. NCDs have been found to exhibit a bright blue emission, but when Fe3+ is added to the NCDs solution the fluorescence intensity of the probe is seen to be quenched. Interestingly, in presence of F- ion the PL of the probe is regenerated. Thus by using fluorescence off-on mechanism present probe was constructed and has been used for the trace detection of F-. UV absorption band of Fe3+ and the fluorescence emission spectra of NCDs overlap to some extent, which suggests an IFE. This effect gets weaken when F- is added. The change in the position of the C = O band n the FTIR spectra suggests the coordination of Fe3+ with the C = O group on the surface of the NCDs. Binding of Fe3+ with the C = O groups on the surface of the NCDs results a large red shift compared to that of the pure NCDs in the UV absorption spectrum, which considerably increases the IFE. But with the addition of F- ions a blue shift in the UV absorption spectrum has been observed indicating the disappearance of IFE effect. Thus quenching occurs due to the IFE and binding of Fe3+ with NCDs. Interestingly, addition of F- to the NCDs/Fe3+ results in the formation of colorless [FeF6]3- complex (Fig. 6
                        ). Thus coordination between Fe3+ and NCDs is found to be decreased and results in the disappearance of the IFE, which restore the PL of NCDs. It is pertinent to mention here that a ready-to-use system i.e. fluorescent test paper has also been developed (Fig. 7
                        ) which can instantly detect Fe3+ and F- with the naked eye.
